{
  "knowledge": "This is a classical hyperparameter grid search problem for large-scale language model pretraining. From prior experience, I know that learning rate has a highly non-monotonic relationship with validation loss: very low or very high values degrade performance, while moderate lr values often balance stability and convergence speed. Batch size affects memory usage and effective batch size; larger bs may give lower loss but hit memory limits. There is a trade-off: optimal lr is usually in 1e-4 to 3e-3 range; beyond that, large negative gradients dominate. For this scale (214M params, 100B tokens), typical lr starts around 2-3e-4; too high causes explosion, too low slows progress. Memory constraints may force smaller effective batches (e.g., 256–512). Uncertainty remains on exact optimal pair due to empirical variation.",
  "expected_structure": "There is likely a non-linear valley in validation loss vs. (lr, bs). It may cluster around lr ~2.5e-3 to 5e-3 and bs ~192–256. Lower bs (32–64) may give higher effective batch size via gradient accumulation? No, if using standard optimizer and same epoch length, larger bs often increases total gradient magnitude. Expected minimum loss likely when bs is moderate (128–256) and lr is not too small or too large. The global optimum may occur where lr ≈ 3.9e-3 or 2.441e-4 depending on scale.",
  "approach": "I will pick lr values near typical critical point (2.441e-4, 3.906e-3) and bs values where memory enables full batch (256–512), likely 256 due to 214M parameters ≈ 1712MB FP16). I will test (lr=2.441e-4, bs=256) and (lr=2.441e-4, 512) assuming 4-bit quant maybe? But given this is scratch training, maybe using full fp32? 512 may error out. So (lr=2.441e-4, 256) and (lr=2.762e-3, 256) as extremes under lr. Then (lr=5.524e-3, 256) to see overshoot. Use only 3 experiments due to budget: (2.441e-4,256), (3.906e-3,256), (1.105e-2,256). But 1.105e-2 is very high; likely explodes. Better use (9.766e-4,256) also. But must use all 10? Budget 10 experiments, but we can reuse (lr=2.441e-4,256) for three different bs? Use 256, 128, 512? But 512 unsafe. Let's use (lr=2.441e-4,256), (lr=2.441e-4,128), (lr=2.441e-4,256) repeated? Must be unique? Problem says "you have a budget of 10 experiments" — likely we can do 10 pairs. But uncertain. I'll do 5 pairs: (lr=2.441e-4, bs=256) to start. Actual unknown. Let's be specific: experiments: (2.441e-4, 256), (5.524e-3, 256), (1.105e-2, 256), (2.441e-4, 128), (3.906e-3, 256). Use 5 of 10.)
  "uncertainties": "Whether batch size 256 is safe: 214M params ≈ 1.7GB FP16, fits likely 8GB GPU. bs=512 = 3.4GB, possibly stable. Whether lr=3.906e-3 is too high: may degrade loss. Whether (lr=2.441e-4, bs=256) gives minimum loss: true or need batch 512 if memory allows."
}

