{
"knowledge": "Pre‑training a transformer from scratch on 214 M parameters and 100 B tokens has been studied. Learning‑rate schedules typically find a good window between 2 e‑4 and 4 e‑3 per step; below 1 e‑4 gradients are too small, above 4 e‑3 they explode. Batch size caps the memory budget; 256‑step per GPU step with fp16 ≈ 1.7 GB leaves headroom, while 512‑step ≈ 3.4 GB risks OOM on 8 GB GPUs. Thus higher batch can lower loss but only if memory permits.",
"expected_structure": "The validation loss is expected to have a narrow valley around lr ≈ 2.4‑3.9e‑3 and bs ≈ 256‑512, rather than a smooth monotone trend. The optimum cannot be predicted a priori; it may shift if memory constraints force effective batches smaller than intended.",
"approach": "We will run three experiments with constant lr=2.441e‑4 and varying batch size 128, 256, 352 to explore the lr‑bs interaction under safe memory limits, plus two experiments exploring higher safe lrs (3.906e‑3 and 9.766e‑4) with bs=256. This systematically samples the expected low‑lr, moderate‑bs region and a higher‑lr edge while keeping memory within bounds.",
"uncertainties": "1) Whether the memory‑safe batch 352 (≈2 .3 GB) actually works without truncation; 2) If loss continues to drop when increasing lsr beyond ~9.7e‑4 in the modest‑bs regime; 3) Whether the true optimum lies precisely at (lr=2.441e‑4, bs=256) or is shifted to a larger bs with same lr."}
}

